				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2831477&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251557" alt="fumeinadebaisu" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2831477)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;" >fumeinadebaisu</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556403337 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Apr 2019 22:15</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4231728">
									

<p>FYI, the original author, <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ailicehershey" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2788062); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2788062&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1556403336" alt="AiliceHershey" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2788062)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ailicehershey" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2788062); return false;">AiliceHershey</a></span>'s announcement of mass-deletion is here:<br />
<a href="http://ja.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-8132146/vol-2#post-4154900">http://ja.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-8132146/vol-2#post-4154900</a></p>
<p>The biggest problem here is that while the author tolerates any form of personal safekeeping of deleted stuff, he also pleaded not to do 'things like asking to repost any of his self-deleted works based on &quot;revive this!!&quot; votes from readers<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-359823-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-359823-1')">1</a></sup>.'</p>
<p>That being said, if you are fluent enough in Japanese, you'd notice there's a great share of ambiguity in his plea; he didn't mention how translated works of those self-deleted articles (finished after the mass-deletion, of course) can be handled.</p>
<p>It even exceed the expectation of the JP's translation guideline, because:</p>
<ol>
<li>there isn't so much self-deletion of articles in the JP branch well above the deletion threshold and/or being there long time,</li>
<li><a href="http://ja.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-2113544/scp-int">explicit permission for the INT wiki</a> exists, but nobody is sure if it stands after his plea for no-repost-request, or it's actually valid for other wikis to have a copy from INT, especially after that plea (it's no way personal, apparently), and</li>
<li>it's not the submitter who translated the article first place<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-359823-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-359823-2')">2</a></sup>.</li>
</ol>
<p>I skimmed over the JP staff wiki for any decision concerning handling of his mass-deletion and plea, and found none.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-359823-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-359823-1')">1</a>. Yes, this actually happened once, and it was for another retiring author. And I think it's unfair to mention that it was based on initiative by staff, rather than the author themself who has mass-deleted, and mainly because it relates at least one Hall of Famer.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-359823-2"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-359823-2')">2</a>. There's much room to give them (the submitter) the benefit of the doubt, by the way. They might have been inactive when he has announced mass-deletion, and if they've seen anything about the mass-deletion later, they might only have found the announcement of deletion, not the earlier, more detailed (IIRC) notice of retirement. Just like me looking for it only to realize it has been made on one of his now-gone articles, perhaps his author's page.</div>
</div>

